tokens.name: This app is for mapping & route following for cycling & walking.
It can be altered to your abilities, so you know whether you till likely be able to complete a route.
It helps  more than, say Google maps as it can show a route away from roads for walking or hiking.
You can track you own routes with photos so others can see what you have don, and you can track your own progress as you try new routes or activities.

It is useful being able to plan a route on your desktop/laptop with a bigger screen, and then transfer to to your phone to use when you are actually out...though it does rely on having a good internet signal, which in remote areas is not always possible.
I like being able to start on my PC and transfer to my phone.
I like being able to see what routes others have done with their photos.
I like being able to see how difficult a route might be, and if I might be able to complete it.
I would like it to be able to work off line for when there is no internet signal.
I am scared of my phone running out of battery before I am complete.
I have privacy worries that others know where I am.
I would like it to use less battery power or work when using air plane mode so the battery will last longer.
I want it to work offline so internet is not always needed.
I don't have a data allowance, so this costs by the minute.
I believe that the Komoot app is a commuting app which lets you do a variety of things regarding commuting.
It lets you select which mode of transport you would like to take and then can provide you with a route between your start position and final destination.
It can consider what roads you would like to use e.g.
quieter roads if commuting by bicycle and footpaths etc.
You can then save these routes and gives you further information, with elevation, distance and likely time to take given.
If you are looking for a local walk or bicycle route, you can also view popular routes planned and used by other users of the app.
These are grouped by beginner, intermediate and advanced routes.
The application also allows you to add pictures so that you can see popular landmarks on the route, and get some idea of location.
I like how you can plan a route, taking into account the type of roads.
I like how you can see other routes from other users.
I like how you can see pictures

I have found it hard to link the app with other apps, such as Strava 
The filters are a bit fiddly on a smartphone 
It sometimes does not take into account changes to the map.
Easily being able to link with other apps such as strava.
Make the filters a bit more user friendly.
Update maps all the time.
The komoot app is an app where users can explore and plan outdoor routes for hiking, biking, camping and other outdoor activities.
Users can view trails and routes suggestions based on their experience.
the app offers a lot of information about the routes such as elevation and surfaces.
Users can share their journeys and trips with others via sharing pictures.
Users can also invite others for a hike or trip.
The app is available on many devices, such as phones, tablets, smart watches.
Maps can be downloaded beforehand so that maps can be viewed offline and help with navigation with the use of GPS.
Users can get weather updates and voice navigation during their trip
I like the offline navigation options that are available on the many different devices.
I also like the different sorts of users the app caters to i.e from begginners to experts and from cyclists to trekkers.
I also like that you can view what the weather will be like during your trip so you can pack and dress accordingly.
I don't like that they offer a subscription.
It should be a pay once and it's yours feature, also for premium features.
It seems like the app and website is trying to be too many things at once.
Some of the social aspects like inviting and sharing trips seems unnecessary.
Those are the only 2 aspects i dislike
The app can be slow to load on some older devices when there is a lot of information to display such as route planner.
If somehow you can only load or filter relevent information that a user selects so that not all routes have to be loaded in the route planner.
In areas with a lot of turns and paths it can be difficult to follow the voice commands which means I have to take out my device to look at the map.
The Komoot App is a phone application that allows route planning and navigation for enjoying and exploring the outdoors.
There are premade routes to choose from that will guide and direct you on your journey with the use of navigation and maps.
You can also log your adventures and share your experiences with friends.
You can even plan the route type and how you will be travelling, eg walking/cycling etc.
You can choose the terrain and sort of ground you will be traversing on.
Yo can even customise your route.
Everything works offline so you don't need to worry about connection to the internet.
I like the ease of being able to plan route and adventures.
I like the style of the app and the green colour palette used as it's close to nature and a feel good colour.
I like that you can customise your route to preferred terrain and type of ground.
Love that it voice navigates.
I'm not keen on the social and sharing aspect of the app.
I don't think there would be enough premade easy routes.
I dislike that you have to sign up to use it.
No sign up.
I really don't want to give my details unless necessary especially to just explore the app and see if I like it.
I also don't like the idea of sharing that I ( a single loan walking woman) walk along a certain route.
Doesn't feel like a very clever or safe idea.
Kommoot App is a mobile app that helps you to discover outdoor routes for hiking, biking, cycling and mountaineering.
It will help you the routes that suit you the best based on your physical shape and your geographic location.
You can use the app to plan the route using a surface and way-point analysis.
The app also shows the elevation profiles and outdoor highlights, which can make your outdoor activities more pleasant and interesting.
You can also read reviews of outdoor points of interest submitted by the users of the app.
The app also syncs our routes and taken pictures with all devices, such as mobile phones, laptops and Android Wear.
I like the ability to sync your data among all the devices that you use.
I like that you can read reviews of outdoor locations submitted by other users.
I like that the app shows the elevation profile of the route.
I do not like some of the interface design choices in the app.
I do not like the the way your data seems to be visible to other users of the app.
I do not like that the prices in the app's shop.
I would lover the prices in the shop.
At the moment, the prices seem to be very high for a niche app like this.
Lower prices would make the app more appealing for a larger number of people.
Komoot supports you to make plans for walks,  hikes, runs or bike rides.
You can use routes that are already in the system or work out new routes.
There is a free and a premium version.

You can set a start and end point and it can work out the distance, and tell you information such as the anticipated length of time as well as the physical distance that would be covered, and the expected fitness level to complete the journey.
You can also follow others, share content and comment on other people's entries.
People add photos of their trips out made using Komoot.
You can use Komoot to record your journeys.
I like the ease of the map, selecting start and end points is very straightforward.
Finding routes is simple - I like that I can choose to start where I am or select somewhere else, so I can think about planning future trips.
I like that it gives me a sense of how challenging a route will be, so I can decide if that route is suitable.
Without paying there is a limited amount you can do.
I do like that I can see the maps, but there is no navigation other than being able to follow your own dot, unless you pay.
And you cannot store a route offiline, which considering how remote many of the walks are is forcing your hand to pay.
I'd like to have more information about things like stiles and if a route is suitable for wheelchairs or pushchairs.
I don't use it for planning routes with some companions for this reason, because I can't see if the route is suitable.
Being able to select routes without stiles, or suitable for wheelchairs/pushchairs.
I have not paid for the app, because I can't see what anything is like - a free trial to see if it is something I would use would be beneficial for people.
I don't want to pay £30 when I don't know what I'm getting.
It's not clear if I'm getting continual access, including updates, for that fee, or if that is for a fixed period of time.
It doesn't make me want to pay premium when it feels very unclear what I'd be getting for that.
It's an app you can use to plan travel, hiking, walking etc.
I think it is geared up for cyclists and walkers etc and can advise on terrain for all parts of the route - grass / paved etc.
You can add in areas you specifically want to travel to or to avoid - or choose the most direct or scenic route.
You can set your own challenges - so you can set goals and it will be able to tell you how far you have achieved them.
It can assign difficulty levels in colour the way you would see on a ski run.
I think you do have to pay a subscription fee to use it and it does have a few rival companies.
It's fantastic for being able to get local knowledge and plan your route according to your own preferences.
I would feel more confident going on my travels due to this and like that you can add or remove places you so or do not with to go to.
There are so many free apps so there's a lot of competition and this app would have to have specific features which are unique to it.
It would be very easily copied and you could find a similar app becomes cheaper elsewhere after you have subscribed.
It could be more competitive on price as there are similar apps out there.
But apart from the competition it has I can't see what they can add as it has so many features already, I think everything is covered.
It is app which bike riding enthusiasts can get together to plan and share routes.
I suppose it helps them build a community together and go on adventures together if they wish.
It can also cater for your level of ability, so if you are very inexperienced, you can go on a more basic ride, or if you are very adventurous, you can plan something much more advanced.
You can also use it to plan walking routes, if you weren’t into cycling.
It might also be helpful if you were lost or in a new area and needed some advice about where to travel.
It would also be a good way of making new friends or contacts in a particular area.
It is free, at least to start with.
I’m not sure how widely used it is, so whether there are actually lots of people on there who you can actually connect with.
It could be aimed even wider, so not just cyclists and walkers, but also horse riders and maybe off road bikers.
Komoot is a popular cycle route planning app.
It was created in 2006 and has over 20million users worldwide.
Once you have planned and set out on your route Komoot takes note of your speed and distance travelled.
Users can also change route easily.
It can be used with mobiles or desktop and navigated when offline for a fee.
Komoot can be used for free at entry point level with paid for features available to purchase at later dates.
It also allows users to add images and reviews of routes and it itself highlights local places of interest along your chosen route.
Komoot is a popular voice for cyclists and is growing at a rapid pace.
I like the fact it is a worldwide app, I don't have to use another when abroad.
I like that I can use it for running as well as cycling usually.
Once you're used to it, it is pretty easy to use.
When I first downloaded it it was pretty hard to get grips on the software.
The accent on the voice navigation!
Sometimes the trips are shorter than I expected.
Usually if I change course while enroute it ends up drastically shorter.
If I could link it to my fitness tracker that would be great.
The komoot app is a very advanced app for people who like to go on adventures on their bike in the UK.
It helps bikers plan their experiences  using the software.
It helps users create their own adventures which match their needs.
They can use the app to discover new locations.
The app also helps users feel like they are part of a community, because they can use the app to share information about their adventures that they have had, along with give tips to other bikers.
Users can use other peoples experiences to see if they want to try riding the same location.
You can explore full routes before going on them.
It's easy to use and navigate.
It serves my purposes, and provides me with more info then I need.
Video coverage, with great graphics
Komoot app is cyckling and hiking navigation and routers planning app, wich working IOS, Android or computer desktop software.

Komoot uses the Opensource OpenStreetMap database for its base mapping but the uses its own algoritms to estanblish tohe best route depending on activity type, selected waypoint and point of interest.
When riding, the Komoot app will tell you speed, distance travelled, distance remaining and let you alter the route on the fly.
You can start using Komoot for free straight away, planning routes and navigation.
Navigate the outdoors even when the internet is down, Offline or unreliable.
Differentiate hiking trails, singletracks, paved roads, mtb trails, terrain and land cover with one glance.
That Komoot is available many devices and that work also offline mode.
Komoot have also community, where you can share your routers and photos your cykling hiking trips to other and get commets for that
Komoot app is expensive and you still get all features your using, than pay full price
Whole app could be lighter to mobile devices, because app to overspend mobiledevices battery
The Komoot app is a nice way to discover walking tracks from all over the world.
You can search for a location and specify what kind of track you are looking for.
Then you can browse tracks and select one to go for.
The app offers navigation and you can export the track to other apps in GPX format.
You can also upload it to your own GPS device.
If you have routes to add you can do this yourself and in this way help other people with your own track information.
The app is available for both Android and Apple IOS.
Some content is available for free, other content is to be paid e.g.
with a subscription.
The enormous amount of tracks that are available is great.
The quality of the tracks is very good.
The app is very user friendly.
With the default settings, they send quite some e-mail.
Not all content is available for free.
Sharing a track is only easy with other people that also have an account.
It would be great to have the Komoot tracks available as an extra layer in e.g.
Google or Apple Maps and then select a track.
Also finding a local guide in a specific area would be a nice plus.
I believe that the Komoot App is a modern navigation app which allows people to plan different routes to locations across the country.
It allows people to organise particular routes using mobile devices or even computer devices as well.
The different routes often include riding types being bus transportation, bike transportation, car transportation or train transportation.
They also provide surfaces and riding abilities which come along with the different methods of transportation when it comes to using the modern navigation app known as Komoot.
This seems to be an excellent way of giving people the chances to choose different route planning techniques over the long term.
I like the fact that it provides plenty of different methods of route planning and also different transportation methods which people can use when using the Komoot App.
I don't really dislike anything about the Komoot App as it does the job it's supposed to do.
Maybe more clear instructions on exactly how to use the Komoot App when it comes to choosing route planning or different transportation methods.
Komoot is just a rather wonderful way of planning and sharing physical activities.
As an avid cyclist, I use Komoot a lot to find interesting ways to get around.
All of it is fully customizable as well, which is a big plus.
Whenever I want a hilly or adventurous route, I can go for that, but when I just want to get from A to B as quickly as I can, that's a possibility too.
The preferable road surface is also a great option they offer.
I also love that the app integrates with most head units (Garmins or things like that), so that I can just pop my phone with the app in my pocket and then follow the route.
All in all, Komoot is just the tool for cyclists, runners, skiers and other outdoor sports lovers.
I just love how versatile Komoot is.
The fact that I can customize every single bit of the route in the way that I prefer it is just wonderful.
You want gravel roads?
You got it.
Tarmac only?
Komoot's got you covered.
I also think that the UI is way better than other similar services.
It's certainly intuitive as far as I'm concerned.
Also, the tool that makes you share routes with your mates is quite cool, so they'll have the route ahead of time.
In terms of dislikes, it still is a platform that is learning and that of course comes with some flaws.
It sometimes sends you up a route that is not suited for cyclists.

Not an issue generally in The Netherlands due to excellent cycling structure, but it did happen to a friend riding in the USA who would have ended up on a major highway if she wasn't more considerate.
Also, the navigation tool is a bit wonky sometimes.
It often happens that it says 'Turn right in 100 metres', only for there to be no such turn.
Other things that irk me a bit are the many updates and the occasional performance issues.
There are times you need to force close the app a few times to get it rolling properly.
The occasional wonky routes that send you on highways could be improved upon massively, although you'd probably be dependent on other companies for that.
The absence of bugs would also be great.
But to be fair, I don't think I'd use Komoot more often even with these fixes.
It's fine as a tool and you can certainly get around while using it.
For routes in familiar areas, I'd use Komoot for planning only and not for the activity itself.
Komoot is an app mainly targeted towards people who enjoy an outdoor, adventurous lifestyle.
On the app, users are able to access a whole host of trails, such as hiking routes, bike routes and mountain biking trails.
It also includes a route planner so people can plan their journey before time in order to make the most of their adventure.
On the route planner, you can put in a starting point and destination and the app will suggest the best route for you to take.
Users are also able to keep a log of all the adventures they've been on to look back on for future reference and to share with their friends.
I like that it allows you to share your experiences with your friends.
It is nice to be able to see routes that have been tried and tested by trusted friends to base decisions on in the future.
I think sometimes there is too much content on the app so it can be difficult to navigate.
If it was easier to navigate, some areas would become more popular as others would be able to see.
The layout of the app could be simplified so that all the information available on the app is clear.
This would allow users to better utilise the app and encourage more use.
It is a navigation app that gives you routes to travel depending on your ability.
You can download the app on the Apple store and you can use it to find routes to travel on doing your fitness.
These routes don’t have to be runs, they can be hikes, riding your bike and things like that.
This app can also connect to other health apps in order to allow you to track your fitness goals.

You can purchase things on the app, and the app has the ability to be shown straight to your Apple Watch which allows you to be able to work out and keep tabs on your time speed and other route related stats along the way.
I like that it is simple to use, has the ability to be modified for the type of exercise you’re doing and that it shows you a route specific to your ability.
The cons of this app is it’s not compatible with all other fitness apps and devices, it sometimes crashes the app and not everything on it is free.
It could be improved by making all content free so that it is more easily accessible by everyone.
Komoot is one of the best apps available in the market that delivers best route planning for mountain bikers, cyclists, backpackers and hikers alike.
It also assists them in navigation.
It helps people to plan new routes, discover new routes, and navigate on a chosen route.
Although, you may find several other apps fulfilling the same purpose like Komoot but what differentiates Komoot from others is that its routing system is very sophisticated than its competitors.
It offers a far more in depth personalisation and auto-generation of the content than a user can view and utilize than any other app in the market.
1) It is very simple and easy to use.
2) It has a lot on offer with respect to personalisation and auto-generated content to explore and utilize.
3) It boasts confidence and provides an opportunity to explore nature as per the user's needs.
4) User experience is enhanced by the Komoot app developers as they keep on bringing in new features from time to time.
5) It offers global coverage and it a bonus for globetrotters provided you live in the region supported by the app.
6) The navigation is clear and simple and is offered in both map and voice guidance and contains clear and concise instructions.
There is hardly anything I dislike about Komoot as there are more things to like than dislike when it comes to Komoot.
However, having said that there are a few things that I do not like.
1) And the first thing is complexity.
Since the app is loaded with so many options, it is sometimes very difficult to build a tour.
Especially, if you are new user, it will take a lot of your time to build tours as you try to sink in all the options related to building tours.
2) Secondly, one of the most important things for apps similar to Komoot to become a popular choice for consumers is to provide health section as an added benefit to increase its popularity.
For example features like number of calories burned, what pace you are traveling in, figuring out heart rates on different levels of the route etc are some of the key features missing from the app.
I seriously think that Komoot should implement these additional features as soon as possible to remain competitive over its competitors and to also benefit the users to a greater extent.
3) The routes that are planned are always not the best.
I think the algorithm used by the app choses the shortest route possible even if it means it is not a safe route to travel with many obstacles included over the best route possible.
So, this is another limitation that the Komoot app has to work on and ensure that the app gives a choice to the user to whether use the best route or the quickest route.
As I mentioned in my dislike section in the previous page there are two things I would like the app to work on as quickly and efficiently as possible.

These features are as follows:

1) Remove complexity from the app.
For a new user, it takes a lot of time to build a tour as there are a lot of options to go through.
So, the developers have to make the process simpler and quicker.
2) Secondly, health and fitness integration is very important for these kind of apps to become successful.
Things like interaction with heart rate monitors, step counters, and features like how many calories burned etc are missing from the app.
I seriously think that Komoot should implement these additional features as soon as possible to remain competitive over its competitors and to also benefit the users to a greater extent.
3) The routes that are planned are always not the best.
I think the algorithm used by the app choses the shortest route possible even if it means it is not a safe route to travel with many obstacles included over the best route possible.
So, this is another limitation that the Komoot app has to work on and ensure that the app gives a choice to the user to whether use the best route or the quickest route.
This will certainly help.
It's an app for hikers/cyclers and helps plan routes for you and routes you may have not taken before, therefore giving you a more exciting time and a bit of an adventure into the bargain.
People can upload different routes and favourite places for you to go to or to ride/hike.
it's also a GPS and can give you voice navigation on where to go and how to get there.
You can also use the app offline to get saved routes or paths.
And can sync it to a headset or helmet and use it that way also.
You can upload files into the route planner and tweak or modify it to use another time or for other people.
It's fast, has a good ui and is easy to use and quite powerful as you can do a lot of different things in the one app instead of having to use multiple different apps for different purposes.
The best thing about it is probably the route planning and offline maps/routes that you can save incase you're not in a good spot for wifi/4g.
It does drain the battery even on standby which isn't a great thing.
The routes could be a bit easier to tweak and modify as it can be a tad clunky.
Uploading files seems to take a few minutes when trying to upload routes.
More routes for planning as it seems like the far out of the way places aren't greatly mapped and I've run in to a few problems that way with dead ends.
More things to connect to like watched and bands.
The Komoot application is an activity tracker and route planner app, slightly similar to STRAVA, Endomondo etc.
It is good because you can set routes before you do them - I think more easily than you can do in strava.
It obviously also records your routes and the statistics from during your route - for example I use it to run and I can see my distance, cadence, speed, route geography (incline etc).
Its good for keeping records this way and also promotes you to do better each time (if you use the same route) as you can save your personal bests etc and try and beat them the next time.
Overall I think its a really good app.

- ease of use 
- focus on more unconventional exercise (hikes etc)
- the ability to use it through my apple account
I don't find the screen and stats as easy to visualise as strava.

the fact some features cost 
I don't like not having the achievements thing that I do with strava
abolishment of in app purchases
The Komoot app is a navigation and route planning app which has routes for you to undertake whether you are walking, cycling, driving etc.
You just choose the area you want to explore and let the app do the rest.
You can also choose the type of ground surface you want to explore to tailor it to your needs.
It allows users to explore new areas and makes planning trips easier.
The app also has a community where users can exchange trip tricks and tips so there is a community feel to the app too.
If you know your start and end points, the app will tell you useful information such as elevation, difficulty etc.
I think the app looks easy to use.

It appears to be very detailed and the information appears kept up to date

The community feel allows important feedback

Don't want to have to set up an account to use

Don't want to pay for premium content

Doesn't always work correctly if no internet

Less paid for content

Link with an existing account eg facebook

Work with apple watch/fitbit and not just garmin
Komoot App is an application and website that provides geolocation services for hikers.
cyclists and other outdoorsy people with specialized maps.
The users should create profiles, which then enables them to log on to komoot website and create routes for their favourite (or selected) activities within desired destination.
The website can then proposes the best path that can be changed manually or depending on inclusion or exclusion of specific features for example excluding highways.
Once o route is selected, it is then presented with road type.
elevation profile, and other relevant information.
Depending on this information and the type of activity, the website also judges how hard or easy it is to journey on this route, and provides an estimated time of completion.
It is then possible to toggle through special icons to see where are public fountains, rest places, etc.
Users can then save the route to be used on their mobile app or paired devices, and share it with other users.
I really like the overall app, especially its route profiling and informative icons on the map.
I also like its navigation feature, I think it is more accurate, especially in urban areas than its competitors.
I like that I can pair it with several other services and devices, which saves me time to download and upload my rides again.
When selecting a route sometimes, for seemingly no apparent reason, it selects the wrong side of the wrong which is in the opposite direction of the designated destination.
So I feel the need to zoom in on every little detail and manually correct it for long rides.

The issue that I complained about, the selection of the wrong side of the road can be improved which would make it use it more often because it would save me time not to correct it manually for every long ride.

Also after I complete a ride, it can ask me if komoot should automatically upload it list of paired services or devices like Strava or Garmin, then at the bottom it can have a checkbox to always upload to X app.
Komoot App is an navigation app that lets riders choose and follow the route based on their skills.
Depending on the users mood, you can choose preexisting routes or completely new ones.
As a rider you can also see what type of terrain you are going through, which can help with reducing the speed and keeping the ride safe.
Unlike numerous apps, Komoot is a voice operated which works offline to aid the rider.
In addition to that, the app also has a social side to it.
It offers a space to share photos of memorable moments through the route.
A great way to connect with people who share similar taste for adventures.

Fitted to ones own riding skills (walking, running, biking, etc)
Works offline
Voice operated
Capability to share photos and connect with people
Terrain information through the route
No option to add favourite such as a home location.

No night mode
Slow to respond on my phone sometimes
My main issue is when you are navigating between the main menu, and it takes quite a while.
It is not such a smooth transition either as it makes me not want to use it anymore.
The Komoot App is a route-planning app, similar to an app called Strava.
It uses GPS to accurately plan routes which can be used for activities such as hiking and running.
It can be used on a smartphone and you can also connect it to an Apple Watch, which can then also be linked to the health app on an Apple iPhone.
The app is free, but there are also paid options where you can unlock the use of offline navigation and voice navigation.
There are also some ready built routes which is a good option for if you’re new to an area and want to find good routes to enjoy nature and the outdoors.
You can save routes and share routes with friends.
The route tracking is more accurate than other apps like Google maps.
The ready-built routes if I want to explore somewhere new.
Ability to share routes with friends.
Scared that my routes somehow become public and strangers will be able to see where I go.
Not all features are free and the paid options are quite expensive.
Need an internet connection which may not be possible in some places.
If the prices were cheaper for the paid options then I would probably purchase to unlock the full use of the app.
Also, sometimes the app crashes so it would be good if the app was constantly updated and working.
It is an app that helps you plan your bike or hiking route.
It helps you plan a route by either inputting your start and end point or you can choose a pre-set route.
There is information about the distance, the time it takes, the types of roads you will be on, the type of ground you will be on and so on.
It is useful because it helps you keep track of where you are going but it also helps you know what to expect while you are riding.
It is also available offline so that you can still get directions and know where you are going even without an internet connection.
Also, you can share pictures and review the route you have taken so that others can see.
I like how easy it is to plan routes.
Just by putting in the start and end point I know exactly what to expect from the route I will be taking.
Second, I love that it is available offline.
I usually have a hard time finding internet connection and I do not have a large data plan so when I am out, I like that I can go back into the app and it still shows me directions.
I also like that I can share pictures and reviews of the routes.
This is how I have found some great routes for me.
If you are using it offline and you go off track, it can be complicated to figure out how to get back on the route without internet.
I would like to have a rating system to show how difficult the route is but also how nice the views are and things like this.
Maybe using icons so that I can easily find what I am looking for.
The road and earth types are a bit difficult to understand.
I am not sure just by looking at the different colours what to expect.
As I mentioned, I think that icons for the reviews would be great.
I think there should be rating on different things such as difficulty, attractiveness of view, maybe even how easy the route is to follow from the app.
This is what I mainly look for in reviews so it would be nice to have this displayed with overall ratings.
The Komoot app is used by walkers and cyclists to help them navigate the outdoor areas they are in.
It can also be used to create new routes and is designed for all levels of ability.
Although the Komoot app is freely available for an iPhone or Android phone, in order to get the full benefits you have to pay an annual fee.
Not cheap though, it costs around £50/$60 per year.
But this option gives access to a huge number of clever features and my favorite is the direction of the wind - it is sometimes possible to always have it behind you!

The Komoot app helps people find enjoyable and scenic routes to bike, hike, and climb.

The routes are described and logged in such a way that people are able to determine which routes they are able to ennjoy, depending on the fitness levels and various capabilities for themselves and members of their parties.
It can suggest routes based on the routes you have enjoyed before.
It logs and tracks the paths you take, so not only is it more difficult to get lost, you can also return to places you have enjoyed before, as all the information is saved.

This app makes things safer and more enjoyable for everyone and brings peace of mind to those who are just beginning their outdoor fitness journeys and novelty and adventure to those who have walked or cycled the same routes for many years.
